         <PROCEDURE>
            <PT_AWARD_CONTRACT_WITHOUT_CALL>
               <D_ACCORDANCE_ARTICLE>
                  <D_TECHNICAL/>
               </D_ACCORDANCE_ARTICLE>
               <D_JUSTIFICATION>
                  <P>The Air Commodities Team, part of the Ministry of Defence,has extended ASCOMM3/566 (PDS) for a maximum of 18 months commencing 1.1.2018 with Drallim Industries Limited to continue the post design services for the support of semi-automatic cargo release units (SACRU) (for the transport of under-slung loads from aircraft) and Aircraft Lashings to secure/release aircraft when embarked on board Royal Navy ships, including;</P>
                  <P>— The provision of custodial and maintenance service for all drawings, specifications and related master documents held against the contract,</P>
                  <P>— The provision of Investigative engineering and engineering support against PDS tasks including defect investigations (MOD F760),</P>
                  <P>— The provision of developmental engineering support tasks,</P>
                  <P>— The design and development of modifications for which Drallim have DAOS approval,</P>
                  <P>— The update of equipment packaging and preparation of prototype packaging specifications,</P>
                  <P>— The supply, on demand, copies of master drawings, prints, specifications, handbooks or reference material,</P>
                  <P>— The preparation and supply of amendments to publications, initial provisioning lists (IPL's) and modification spares provisioning lists (MSPL's),</P>
                  <P>— The upgrade and modification of the SACRUs to include the EMC protected solenoid (to prevent inadvertent release of cargo) and STANAG 3542 compliant load beam with keeper.</P>
                  <P>It is considered that this contract can be placed using the negotiated procedure without prior publication of a contract notice pursuant to Article 32(2)(b)(ii) of Directive 2014/24/EU of the European Parliament and of the Council (Regulation 32(2)(b)(ii) of the UK Public Contracts Regulations 2015) for technical reasons. This is due to Drallim Industries Limited being the Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM), and the only company to have produced and supported this equipment since its introduction, and a number of the equipment components listed are only supplied or licensed by this Company. As such Drallim Industries Limited is currently the only company with the experience, product knowledge and historical data required to undertake PDS. Failure to provide these services is likely to result in the operational capability of Aircraft being restricted to non-load carrying roles and the Authority being unable to fulfil its mandated obligations.</P>
                  <P>Obtaining this equipment from another economic operator would require technical approval, which is a complex process, in accordance with Military Aviation Authority (MAA) regulations and TAA approvals with an estimated timeframe of 18 to 24 months prior to approval being granted for each aircraft platform, (5 in all), accompanied by a cost commensurate with the timeframe It would not be possible to ensure that another economic operator could be sufficiently qualified, within the timeframe to undertake the spares support activities without incurring an unacceptable level of risk. This delay would result in the Authority not being able to fulfil safety requirements that must be adhered to in order to ensure the safe operation of the associated platforms and aircraft systems within an Airworthy environment.</P>
               </D_JUSTIFICATION>
